   Delaware Transportation Authority -- $130 million of
transportion system senior revenue bonds, 1990 Series, due
July 1, 1991-2004 and 2010, tentatively priced by a Dillon
Read &amp; Co. group to yield from 5.90% in 1991 to 7.40% in
2010. Current interest serial bonds are priced to yield from
5.90% in 1991 to 7.25% in 2004. There is $58.2 million of 6
3/4% term bonds priced to yield 7.40% in 2010. The bonds are
rated single-A-1/double-A-minus.
   State of New York Mortgage Agency -- $123 million of
homeowner mortgage revenue bonds, Series RR, due Oct. 1, 2010
and 2017, and Series SS, due April 1 and Oct. 1, 1992-2000,
and Oct. 1, 2019 and 2022, tentatively priced by a Bear
Stearns &amp; Co. group to yield from 6.20% in 1992 to 7.95% in
2022. Series RR consists of $28.5 million of 7.65% term bonds
priced at par due in 2010. There also is $36.4 million of 7
3/4% term bonds priced at par due in 2017. Series SS current
interest serial bonds are priced at par to yield from 6.20%
in 1992 to 7.20% in 2000. There are $15.7 million of 7 1/2%
term bonds priced par due in 2019 and $28.2 million of 7.95%
term bonds priced at par due in 2022. Interest on the Series
SS bonds will be treated as a preference item in calculating
the federal alternative minimum tax that may be imposed on
certain investors. Series RR bonds are not subject to the
tax. The bonds are rated double-A/double-A.
   Clark County, Nev. -- $53.8 million of transportation
improvement limited tax bonds, Series 1990, due March 1 and
Sept. 1, 1991-2000, via a Clayton Brown &amp; Associates Inc.
group. The bonds, which are insured and triple-A-rated, were
priced for reoffering to yield from 5.90% for bonds due March
1, 1991, to 6.95% for bonds due March 1 and Sept. 1, 1999.
Bonds due in 2000 were not formally reoffered.
                                                                                                       


                                                                                                       

   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $501 million of
floating-rate and inverse floating-rate funding note
pass-through certificates issue, Series 195, via Lehman
Brothers. The offering is backed by 9% Freddie Mac giant
mortgage participation certificates provided by Structured
Asset Securities Corp., a subsidiary of Lehman Brothers. The
offering consists of four recombinable inverse floater
classes and one floating-rate class, each representing
ownership interests in one of five individual funding notes.
The coupon rate of each recombinable inverse floater class
resets quarterly based on changes in the three-month London
interbank offered rate and a multiplier formula. All classes
pay principal and interest quarterly.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $500 million of
Remic mortgage securities offered in 12 classes by Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. The offering, Series 1990-116, was priced Aug.
16. It is backed by Fannie Mae 9% securities with a weighted
average coupon rate of 9% and weighted average remaining term
to maturity of 29.58 years.
   Shawmut National Remic Trust 1990-A -- $218 million of
home equity loan pass-through certificates, via Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. The securities have a coupon rate of 9.15% and
are priced at 99 25/32 to yield 9.26%, or 100 basis points
above the interpolated two-year and three-year Treasury notes
yield. The seller of the underlying home equity loans is
Shawmut Bank, and the servicer of the loans is Connecticut
National Bank. The securities have an expected average life
of 2.5 years based on an annual prepayment rate of 20%.
Expected final maturity is July 15, 1997. Legal final
maturity is Nov. 15, 2005. Connecticut National Bank and
Shawmut Bank are units of Shawmut National Corp., Hartford,
Conn.
                                                                                                       

