<HL>
   Trump Bailout
   Wins Approval
   Of Casino Panel
   ---
   But Commission Chairman
   Says Plan Won't Resolve
   All of Developer's Woes
   ----
   By Neil Barsky
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   X.TMP BT
</CO>
<IN>
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)
BANKS (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   The New Jersey Casino Control Commission unanimously
approved Donald J. Trump's $65 million bank bailout, though
the commission chairman cautioned that the plan wouldn't
resolve all of the developer's financial troubles.
   The approval caps three months of arduous negotiations
that led to the agreement that restructured about $2 billion
of Mr. Trump's $3.2 billion of casino and bank debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition to lending him $65 million, the banks will
suspend about $850 million in interest payments for the next
three to five years. In return, Mr. Trump gave the banks
second mortgages on almost all his assets, including his
three Atlantic City casinos. He also agreed to stringent
financial controls, including limits on his personal
spending.
   On Monday night, Mr. Trump reached an agreement with a
group of subcontractors that is owed about $70 million for
its work on Mr. Trump's Taj Mahal casino. Persons close to
the negotiations said the contractors accepted 20%, or about
$14 million, now with the rest of the payments deferred over
five years.
   Mr. Trump's next step is expected to be a restructuring of
the remaining $1.2 billion in casino debt. As part of its
approval, the commission set a relicensing hearing within
three weeks to evaluate the financial stability of Mr.
Trump's three casinos.
   "I do not view this restructuring as the total solution to
the problem," Valerie Armstrong, the acting commission
chairwoman, said.
   In preparation for Mr. Trump's bond restructuring
proposal, Taj Mahal bondholders yesterday retained Rothschild
Inc. as their investment adviser.
   Because they hold first-mortgage bonds, the Taj
bondholders believe they are in a stronger position than Mr.
Trump.
   "At the end of the day, we think Mr. Trump is a pragmatist
and at the end of the day the banks are pragmatic too," said
Wilbur Ross, a debt restructuring specialist with Rothschild.
In the past, Mr. Trump has said that if the Taj is forced to
file for bankruptcy-court protection, bondholders won't
receive interest or equity for three years.
   Mr. Trump said he was happy with the commission's
decision. "It was a wonderful victory. I'm very happy with
the decision," he said.
   Essentially, Mr. Trump's advisers said, the commission's
approval is a sign it believes many of the developer's
problems may be solved if he is given breathing room.
   "After balancing the issues, the commission felt it was
better for the bank deal to go forward and give Mr. Trump the
opportunity to deal with his Atlantic City situation," said
Nicholas Ribis, Mr. Trump's New Jersey attorney who argued
Mr. Trump's case before the commission.
   Many of the bankers and lawyers involved said the bailout
was one of the most complex corporate restructurings they
ever worked on. Close to 90 lending institutions were party
to the bailout, and about 1,000 lawyers, bankers and
accountants participated in the talks. Over the past week,
Mr. Trump spent much of his time in the Manhattan law offices
of Wachtell Lipton Rosen &amp; Katz, where he personally signed
close to 2,000 documents.
   Wachtell represents Bankers Trust Corp. which, in addition
to being one of Mr. Trump's most exposed creditors, is acting
as agent for the other banks.
   Wachtell is also one of about a dozen law firms which have
run up a total of about $10 million in legal fees, according
to persons involved in the negotiations. In a debt
restructuring, legal fees are traditionally paid for by the
debtor, although recently released financial documents show
Mr. Trump may not have the funds to pay the banks' lawyers.
   The banks attorneys are believed to be working on a
payment schedule that mirrors somewhat the arrangement
reached last night with Mr. Trump's unpaid subcontractors.
   According to persons familiar with the arrangement, Mr.
Trump will give the bank attorneys one-third of their fees
now, another third in April and the remainder in June. Should
Mr. Trump not be able to pay the fees, the attorneys will
still most likely be paid by the banks, said a person
familiar with the negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900822-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900822-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Ends Lower as Afternoon Rally
   Fails to Offset Early Morning Plunge
   ----
   By Howard Hoffman
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Even a rebound from a steep morning decline couldn't
inspire much positive comment about the over-the-counter
stock market yesterday.
   Traders noted that the OTC's major index regained about
25% of its first-hour loss, but found little reason for
optimism in the face of the crisis in the Persian Gulf.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Nasdaq Composite Index lost 8.91, or 2.3% and closed
at 379.68, its third consecutive loss. The index had fallen
about 13 points before a late morning rally.
   At the opening bell, OTC stocks followed the Big Board
lower, recording major losses in the first hour of trading.
Both rallied at midday. But while the listed stocks fell in
the afternoon, OTC stocks eased higher.
   The New York Stock Exchange Composite Index closed 1.9%
lower. The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 52.48, a 2%
loss.
   Traders are at a loss to explain the upward creep of the
OTC market in the afternoon while Big Board stocks languished
lower.
   John Schraff, an equities trader for Daiwa Securities
America, suggests it may be merely a matter of timing.
   "Secondary issues were beat up a lot worse," Mr. Schraff
says. "They may be seeing their bottoms at different times."
   At Alex. Brown &amp; Sons, William Rothe, managing director of
equity trading, saw some short-covering in OTC issues and a
few investors picking up a rare bargain.
   "The mood still remains cautious," Mr. Rothe says. "It
will take good news out of the Middle East to get some form
of technical rally."
   Volume increased dramatically to 166.4 million shares from
Monday's paltry 115.5 million shares. Decliners led advancing
issues 1,747 to 458.
   MCI Communications was by far the most active OTC issue.
MCI traded 3.7 million shares, nearly double its daily
average of 2.1 million shares.
   Much of the interest in MCI began with its morning
announcement that it might write off about $500 million in
the third quarter to convert its analog systems to digital.
MCI also said it would spend about $1.1 billion in 1991 on
the conversion.
   The market sent MCI about two points lower at the outset.
By afternoon, investors began buying and nearly cut MCI's
decline in half. It finished the day at 33 5/8, down 1 1/8.
   Gaining issues weren't easy to find on the closing tape.
But late shopping in some technology issues pushed Novell 1
5/8 higher to 22 3/4 and Oracle Systems 1/8 higher to 13 5/8.
Sun Microsystems reversed early losses to end unchanged at
26.
   Alex. Brown's Mr. Rothe suggests that investors looking
for selective opportunities may be scouring the roles of the
battered technology issues for a bargain or two.
   Of course, not all technology stocks avoided declines.
Intel lost 1 to 32 1/4. Apple Computer fell 1/2 to 36 1/4.
Microsoft also rebounded from early lows but still closed 1
1/4 lower at 54 1/4.
   Cellular stocks suffered too. McCaw Cellular declined 1/2
to 18 3/4. LIN Broadcasting fell 1 5/8 to 57. Contel Cellular
was down 1 3/4 to 14. Nationwide Cellular Service stumbled 1
to close at 4 3/4.
   Big losses were abundant in virtually every OTC sector.
Two athletic-shoe makers fell drastically. Nike was off 5 7/8
to 67 3/8 while K-Swiss lost 1 3/4 to 18 1/2. The British
information and trading systems giant, Reuters, gave up
ground again, dropping another 2 points to close at 44 3/4.
And International Lease Finance dropped 1 1/2 to 27 1/2.
   Brand was down 1 1/2 to 13 1/4. Dow Jones Professional
Investor Report said the company told analysts its third
quarter earnings might be lower than expected.
   Cetus fell 1 1/8 to 7 1/2. The New York Times reported the
company is in trouble following management changes, layoffs
and Food and Drug Administration questions about its most
important product, interleukin-2.
   Stuart Hall reported it was negotiating with an investor
group to sell a 7% stake in the company. Stuart Hall said the
investor group might be interested in acquiring the entire
company eventually. Stuart Hall shares rose 5/8 to 10 5/8.
   Prospect Group traded more than 10 times its average daily
volume as the company began distribution of its assets as it
liquidates. Prospect Group shareholders will receive both
cash and the stock of subsidiaries. The company's shares fell
5/8 to 2 1/8 on 1.6 million shares.
   Buy-backs brought disparate responses.
   Dionex shares were 1/8 lower at 18 7/8 despite the
company's announcement that it would buy back as many as one
million of its 8.9 million common shares.
   Andrew added 3/4 to close at 18 on news the company would
repurchase one million of its 10.2 million common shares
outstanding.
</TEXT>
