<HL>
   Business Brief -- Dayton Hudson Corp.:
   Profit Rise of 7% Posted
   Despite Acquisition Costs
</HL>
<DATE>
08/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   DH
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
</IN>
<LP>
   Dayton Hudson Corp. said net income rose 7% in the fiscal
second quarter, despite the negative impact of its recent
acquisition of the Marshall Field's department store chain.
   The Minneapolis-based retailer earned $59.8 million, or 75
cents a share, for the period ended Aug. 4, compared with $56
million, or 72 cents a share, a year earlier. The Field's
acquisition reduced earnings in the quarter by about 15 cents
a share, the company said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Revenue for the period rose 3.2% to $3.2 billion from $3.1
billion.
   The company said it expects the Field's acquisition to
reduce earnings in the third and fourth quarters by a total
of five cents a share. The company said interest and
depreciation expenses related to the Field's acquisition
would offset Field's contribution to operating earnings in
1990.
   For the first six months, Dayton Hudson said net income
rose 28% to $123.9 million, or $1.56 a share, from $96.8
million, or $1.23 a share. The latest period includes a net
gain of $6.6 million, or nine cents a share, for accounting
changes.
   Revenue in the six months rose nearly 6% to $6.25 billion
from $5.92 billion.
</TEXT>
