<HL>
   International Brief -- Pakhoed Holding N.V.:
   Merger Talks Being Held
   With Another Dutch Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
08/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   N.PAK Y.FUR N.VOM N.KNG N.INM
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Pakhoed Holding N.V., a Dutch transport and tank storage
concern, said it is holding merger talks with Furness N.V., a
Dutch shipping company.
   Dutch analysts said that if the merger proceeds, as
expected, this would complete a long-term consolidation with
four Dutch companies effectively running stevedoring services
in Rotterdam, Europe's largest port: Pakhoed, Van Ommeren
Ceteco N.V., Koninklijke Nedlloyd Groep N.V. and
Internatio-Muller N.V.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the terms being discussed, Pakhoed would offer one
share or certificate of share in Pakhoed plus 130 guilders
for two shares or certificates of shares in Furness, which
analysts valued at 140 million guilders ($79.4 million) to
160 million guilders.
   Separately, Pakhoed posted a 64% increase in first-half
profit to 69.2 million guilders, including a gain of 8.7
million guilders from an asset sale, from 42.2 million
guilders a year earlier, when Pakhoed had a net loss from
extraordinary items of 1.2 million guilders. Excluding
extraordinary items, Pakhoed's profit from ordinary
operations rose 39% to 60.5 million guilders from 43.4
million guilders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900822-0016
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900822-0016.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
08/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH REJECTED an Iraqi offer to negotiate as he prepared
to call up reserves.
   The president was expected to sign an order today
activating military reserve specialists as the White House
declared that "the world is united" in demanding the
unconditional withdrawal of Saddam Hussein's army from
Kuwait. Amid mounting tensions, the State Department
confirmed that at least 54 Americans are believed to be in
Iraqi custody. Bolstering the U.S. effort to choke Iraq
economically, nine West European nations authorized their
warships in the Persian Gulf to use force to back U.N.
sanctions against Iraq. U.S. officials said that Navy
interdiction efforts have forced many Iraqi vessels to stay
away from ports.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a speech directed to Bush, Saddam Hussein defended
Iraq's detainment of foreigners and promised "a major
catastrophe" if fighting breaks out.
   ---
   Most East German parties agreed to set an Oct. 14 date to
unify their nation with West Germany. But hours later, the
Social Democrats said they wanted the date set a month
earlier and would challenge the accord signed by their
leader, who said he was resigning as chief of his faction in
Parliament.
   ---
   European Community officials unveiled their final
blueprint for monetary union. The EC executive commission's
plan calls for setting up an EC central bank by Jan. 1, 1993,
in preparation for establishing a common monetary policy and
the European Currency Unit as a single currency in the
12-nation bloc.
   ---
   Government and black leaders made a plea for peace in the
South African townships around Johannesburg as the death toll
from 10 days of tribal violence surpassed 400. The joint plea
was issued by President de Klerk, Zulu leader Buthelezi and
Xhosa leader Holomisa in an effort to halt clashes between
Zulus and Xhosas.
   ---
   The Indian parliament approved presidential rule in the
state of Jammu and Kashmir, and gave the armed forces special
powers there, according to local radio reports. Indian
officials said tanks and troop reinforcements were dispatched
to the frontier with Pakistan, where soldiers from the two
countries clashed this week.
   ---
   Armenia's Parliament debated an independence declaration
and considered setting up an army for protection from
neighboring Azerbaijan, the Soviet news agency Tass said.
Azerbaijan's leader responded by calling for sanctions
against Armenia and warning that his republic might be forced
to take steps to guarantee its security.
   ---
   A federal AIDS panel said the disease is growing at an
alarming rate in rural America, but treatment is complicated
by "fear and bigotry." The National Commission on AIDS also
said that federal clinical trials designed to speed approval
of AIDS drugs were flawed and that many health-care workers
won't treat AIDS patients.
   ---
   A jury in Miami began deciding whether Eugene Hasenfus and
another Contra supply crew member shot down in 1986 in
Nicaragua deserve to be compensated for risking their lives
in the White House-sanctioned operation. Attorneys for
Southern Air Transport and other defendants say Hasenfus was
aware of the covert flight's risks.
   ---
   Leftist guerrillas stepped up attacks on government troops
throughout El Salvador as hopes waned for a cease-fire accord
in the latest round of discussions aimed at ending the
10-year civil war. The rightist Cristiani government and the
insurgents have been holding peace talks in Costa Rica.
   ---
   An African peacekeeping force prepared to board ships in
Sierra Leone bound for Liberia, where the multinational
military group will try to halt an eight-month civil war. The
hundreds of soldiers were expected to depart for Monrovia
today.
   ---
   A National Research Council study gave a boost to
proponents of small satellites, who have criticized plans to
spend as much as $50 billion over 25 years on huge satellites
to study the earth's climate. For the coming fiscal year, the
Bush administration is seeking $235 million for the larger
Earth Observing Systems.
   ---
   Maoist rebels blacked out much of Peru and set off two car
bombs in Lima in support of a one-day national strike called
to protest austerity measures announced Aug. 8 by the new
Fujimori government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900822-0015
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900822-0015.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   USAir to Dismiss
   1,500 Employees;
   More Cuts Expected
   ----
   By Asra Q. Nomani and Francine Schwadel
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   U LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   ARLINGTON, Va. -- USAir Group Inc. said it is dismissing
about 1,500 employees in another cutback at the airline
holding company. USAir also lost a bitter union battle.
   The airline said yesterday that the fired "employees were
hired in anticipation of an expansion program that has since
been reduced in light of current economic projections."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A spokeswoman said the 1,500 employees, including pilots,
flight attendants and customer service agents, represent
about 3% of the company's work force. Most of the employees
are considered "probationary," meaning they haven't completed
a probationary period that the company said typically lasts
six months.
   The move follows an earlier cutback. Last week, the
company confirmed that it is furloughing 211 pilots starting
Jan. 1. The company yesterday indicated there is more to
come, saying: "Additional reductions in personnel will be
announced as determined."
   Most U.S. carriers are anticipating that a downturn in the
economy will hurt traffic growth over the next few years, but
none have acted as swiftly as ailing USAir.
   USAir has said it is going through a "detailed review" of
its plans for the next 12 to 24 months. Already the company
said it has dropped plans to start new service to certain
cities, which it refuses to identify.
   The airline is also expected to reduce its fleet. Industry
analysts say the carrier will probably retire older planes
earlier than planned and defer deilvery of options to buy
planes. Earlier this summer, USAir postponed until 1995
delivery of a dozen Boeing Co. 737s that it had planned to
receive in 1991 and 1992.
   The company has been struggling since it merged its newly
acquired Piedmont Aviation unit into USAir last August. In
the first quarter, it suffered heavy losses amid widespread
customer service problems in areas such as on-time
performance and baggage delivery. Second-quarter operating
income of $59 million fell far below year-ago performance of
$201 million.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, USAir
shares dropped 75 cents to close at $16.875.
   Separately, the National Mediation Board ruled that USAir
"tainted the laboratory conditions necessary" for a fair
union representation election. The Teamsters union claimed
that USAir had illegally interfered with the union's campaign
to represent about 8,000 fleet service workers.
   A USAir spokeswoman said, "We regret the decision." She
declined to comment further.
   The board, which governs labor-management relations in the
airline and railroad industries, said the Teamsters could
seek a new election. The Teamsters hailed the decision as a
victory, and said it plans to wage "an all-out campaign" to
represent USAir workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
