<HL>
   Who's News:
   Hawaiian Electric
   Says Pratt to Retire
   From Parent, Unit
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
08/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   HE WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   C. Dudley Pratt Jr., president and chief executive of
Hawaiian Electric Industries Inc. and chief executive of its
Hawaiian Electric Co. subsidiary, said he will retire from
those posts at the end of the year.
   Mr. Pratt, 62 years old, advanced his plans by one year
after he was nominated to become one of four trustees of an
estate that is the second-largest landowner in the Hawaiian
Islands.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Pratt will remain a director of the Honolulu-based
holding company, which was formed in 1981.
   Robert F. Clarke, group vice president-diversified
companies, has been named to succeed Mr. Pratt as president
and chief executive of the holding company. Mr. Clarke, 48,
joined the company in 1987 as vice president of strategic
planning and helped to implement the company's successful
diversification strategy.
   Edward J. Blackburn, currently president and chief
executive of Hawaiian Insurance &amp; Guarantee Co., a Hawaiian
Electric Industries unit, will succeed Mr. Clarke as group
vice president-diversified companies.
   Thomas S. Adams, senior vice president of Hawaiian
Insurance &amp; Guarantee, will succeed Mr. Blackburn as the
insurance company's president and chief executive. Harwood D.
Williamson, group vice president-utility companies, who is
also president of Hawaiian Electric Co., assumes the
additional post of chief executive of the utility company
from Mr. Pratt.
   Hawaiian Electric Industries provides electric service to
96% of the residents of the Hawaiian Islands and also has
interests in financial services, maritime transportation and
real estate development.
</TEXT>
